        <section>
            <h2>What is the Waterfall Model?</h2>
            <p>
                The Waterfall Model is a traditional software development approach that follows a linear and sequential process. Each stage of development must be completed before the next stage begins, similar to water flowing downward through a series of steps. Because of this structure, the model does not allow much flexibility or major changes once development has started. This method emphasizes careful planning, clear documentation, and defined milestones throughout the project. As a result, teams can easily track progress and maintain a predictable development schedule.
            </p>
        </section>
        <img src="img/clker-free-vector-images-waterfall-310140.png" alt="Waterfall Image" class="waterfall-image">
        <section>
            <h2>Phases of the Waterfall Model</h2>
            <p>
                The Waterfall Model divides the development process into several sequential phases. The process begins with requirements analysis, where the development team gathers and documents the customer’s needs. Next is the design phase, where the system architecture and technical details are planned. After the design is complete, developers move into the implementation phase, where the software is built and individual components are tested. The completed system then goes through testing and deployment, ensuring that the software works correctly before being released to users. Finally, the maintenance phase involves fixing issues, improving performance, and updating the system after deployment. 
            </p>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Advantages and Use Cases</h2>
            <p>
                The Waterfall Model is valued for its simplicity and clear structure. Because each phase has defined goals and documentation, it is easy for teams to understand the project workflow and monitor progress. This structured approach also encourages careful planning and organized development practices. However, the model works best when project requirements are well-defined and unlikely to change. It is commonly used for smaller projects or situations where strict documentation and predictable timelines are required.
            </p>
        </section>
